Hi
   If using "char *" in dpi function, the function will become c++ symbol, rather than c

```
import "DPI-C" function int add(input int a, input int b);
import "DPI-C" function void profile (input string str);
```

```
int add(int a, int b)
{
	printf("add ar\n");
	return a + b;
}

void profile(char *str){
	printf("quantr %s\n", str);
}
```

nm ./obj_dir/sim_main.o|grep 'add\|profile'

```
0000000000000028 T add
0000000000000042 T _Z7profilePc
```

Then if i link it, it will said:

/usr/bin/ld: Vquantr_i_main__ALL.a(Vquantr_i_main___024unit__DepSet_h947cdc23__0.o): in function `Vquantr_i_main___024unit____Vdpiimwrap_profile_TOP____024unit(std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> >)':
Vquantr_i_main___024unit__DepSet_h947cdc23__0.cpp:(.text+0x11): undefined reference to `profile'

here is generated header

```
// Verilated -*- C++ -*-
// DESCRIPTION: Verilator output: Prototypes for DPI import and export functions.
//
// Verilator includes this file in all generated .cpp files that use DPI functions.
// Manually include this file where DPI .c import functions are declared to ensure
// the C functions match the expectations of the DPI imports.

#ifndef VERILATED_VQUANTR_I_MAIN__DPI_H_
#define VERILATED_VQUANTR_I_MAIN__DPI_H_  // guard

#include "svdpi.h"

#ifdef __cplusplus
extern "C" {
#endif


    // DPI IMPORTS
    // DPI import at src-output/quantr_dpi.h:1:29
    extern int add(int a, int b);
    // DPI import at src-output/quantr_dpi.h:2:30
    extern void profile(const char* str);

#ifdef __cplusplus
}
#endif

#endif  // guard
```

thanks
